<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO CHET</font><br>
<tt>Tue Oct 28 21:44:07 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
<br>
Chet,<br><br>
I'm Paul, one of the new guys on this site.  I read with interest your last post.  I thought you made lots of good points.<br><br>
I was twenty years and six months old when I returned from Vietnam.  It was a week before Christmas in 1967.<br><br>
Here are a few thoughts from almost thirty years ago.<br><br>
Then I came back and said to myself that I have no heart. The last few months in Vietnam I said the night belongs to me.  That was part of what I became.  I was good at what I did.  I was a Wolfhound in Cu Chi.  That's a raw emotion.<br><br>
We all are supposed to lose our innocence along the parth of life, and yes I wish it hadn't been so abrupt and with so much force, but I feel an extreme amount of pride in that I survived and am surviving still.  Anger, angst and frustration comes from an idealistic belief that all of our lives (vet and non vet) could be so easy if _____.  You fill in the blank.<br><br>
I went to the library shortly after I came home and saw the book HEART OF DARKNESS on the shelf.  The title reminded me of Vietnam.  I took it home and read it and told myself -- that's Vietnam -- forget Africa.  That was before the movie was made.<br><br>
TIME HAS COME TODAY by the Chambers Brothers is the song that best describes Vietnam.  I have the record and play it occasionally.  I will probably dig it out after I finish these thoughts.<br><br>
I recently wrote on another thread that Vietnam gave me more than it took from me.  I sincerely believe that and people I've known over the years have benefited from what I &quot;learned&quot; over there.  Although I will readily admit that it took a long time for me to adjust.<br><br>
I have physical scars on my body -- not from the war.  I was lucky enough to have made it home without a Purple Heart.  The scars are a part of the history of Paul, so are the psychological/emotional scars of the war.<br><br>
I went to a vet rap group many years ago and I was the one with the most intensity.  I said at that time that I would no longer let the Vietnam War get the better of me.  I like to think that I &quot;beat it.&quot;<br><br>
I wrote on another thread that there are times when I feel the words of Chief Joseph, in that I WILL FIGHT NO MORE FOREVER.  And yet there are other times when my fist clenches when people can't/don't along and want to create more deadly drama and say &quot;you have to go through me first before that BS will start again.&quot;<br><br>
Please understand, that I am not disagreeing with you.  I want to hear opinions other than my own.  I said that before too.  The site will take it's own course with yours and my input both.  I will look in the future at some of the past threads and see if I can stretch them to a different point.  This site is all of our chances to add to history and no matter which way it goes it will have accomplished it purpose.<br><br>
My best to you.  I will reread some of your past posts so that I might get to know you better.<br><br>
Paul<br><br>
P.S.  I ran on again.
